3 DATA WRANGLING PROCESS

3.1 Factorize nominal variables

# Convert non-numerical variables to factor and "NA" to number
training <- training %>%
  mutate(host_id = as.factor(host_id),
         neighbourhood = as.factor(neighbourhood),
         room_type = as.factor(room_type),
         last_review = ymd(last_review),
         reviews_per_month = ifelse(is.na(reviews_per_month), 0, reviews_per_month)
         )

3.2 Basic calculation of given variables

# Calculate the distance to city center
lat_center <- 41.8781 # Latitude of Chicago city center
lon_center <- -87.6298 # Longtitude of Chicago city center
training <- training %>%
  mutate(distance_center = distHaversine(
    cbind(longitude, latitude),
    c(lon_center, lat_center) ) / 1000) # Create new variable: distance_center (Unit: km)

3.3 Handle outliers

# Handling outliers using the IQR technique
cols <- c("availability_365", "price", "reviews_per_month", 
          "number_of_reviews", "minimum_nights", "calculated_host_listings_count","distance_center")

bounds <- list()
for (i in cols) {
  Q1 <- quantile(training[[i]], 0.25, na.rm = TRUE)
  Q3 <- quantile(training[[i]], 0.75, na.rm = TRUE)
  IQR <- Q3 - Q1
  
  bounds[[i]] <- list(
    lower = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR,
    upper = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
  )
}
# Replace outliers by lower or upper bounds
  training_clean <- training
    for (i in cols) {
      lower_bound <- bounds[[i]]$lower
      upper_bound <- bounds[[i]]$upper
    
  training_clean <- training_clean %>%
    mutate(
      !!i := case_when(
      .data[[i]] < lower_bound ~ lower_bound,
      .data[[i]] > upper_bound ~ upper_bound,
      TRUE ~ .data[[i]]
      )
    )
}

# Check skewness

# Heatmap
# Convert matrices to long format
r_long <- melt(r)
p_long <- melt(p)

# Combine correlation and p-value data
heatmap <- left_join(r_long, p_long, by = c("Var1", "Var2"))
colnames(heatmap) <- c("x", "y", "r", "p")

# Create significance stars
heatmap$stars <- ifelse(heatmap$p < 0.001, "***",
             ifelse(heatmap$p < 0.01, "**",
             ifelse(heatmap$p < 0.05, "*", "")))

# Plot using ggplot2
ggplot(heatmap, aes(x, y, fill = r)) +
  geom_tile(color = "white") +
  scale_fill_gradientn(colors = rev(colorRampPalette(brewer.pal(9, "RdYlBu"))(200))) +
  geom_text(aes(label = round(r, 2)), size = 2.5, color = "black") +           # correlation values
  geom_text(aes(label = stars, y = as.numeric(y) + 0.25),                    # stars (offset upward)
            color = "black", size = 2.5) +
  coord_fixed() +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 12) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 1, hjust = 1),
        axis.title = element_blank()) +
  labs(title = "Correlation Matrix with Significance Stars",
       fill = "r")

5 MODELLING

5.1 Splitting data

set.seed(9)
cv_split <- initial_split(training_clean, prop = 0.75, strata = price)
train <- training(cv_split)
validate <- testing(cv_split)

5.2 Linear regression

# 1. Preprocess data (Recipe)
rec <- recipe(price ~ log_minimum_nights + number_of_reviews + reviews_per_month +
    log_calculated_host_listings_count + availability_365 +
    room_type + neighbourhood + distance_center, data = train) %>%     
  step_novel(all_nominal_predictors()) %>% # assign a previously unseen factor level to a new value
  step_lencode_glm(neighbourhood, outcome = vars(price)) %>%
  step_lencode_glm(room_type, outcome = vars(price)) %>%
  step_zv(all_predictors()) %>% # remove variables that contain only a single value
  step_normalize(all_predictors()) # scale predictors only

# 2. Specify model

lm_spec <- linear_reg() %>% 
  set_mode("regression") %>%
  set_engine("lm")

# 3. Create workflow

lm_wf <- workflow() %>%
  add_model(lm_spec) %>%
  add_recipe(rec)

# 4. Do cross validation / bootstrapping
# 5. Define values to be explored
# 6. Tune model

# 7. Fit data to model
wf_fit <- fit(lm_wf, data = train)

# 1. Preprocessing data (recipe)
ridge_recipe <-
  recipe(formula = price ~ availability_365 + log_calculated_host_listings_count + log_minimum_nights + number_of_reviews + reviews_per_month + neighbourhood + distance_center + room_type, data = train) %>%
  step_novel(all_nominal_predictors()) %>% # assign a previously unseen factor level to a new value
  step_lencode_glm(neighbourhood, outcome = vars(price)) %>%
  step_lencode_glm(room_type, outcome = vars(price)) %>%
  step_zv(all_predictors())  %>% # remove variables that contain only a single value
  step_normalize(all_predictors()) # scale predictors only

  linear_reg(mixture = 0, penalty = tune()) %>%

  set_engine("glmnet")

5.9 XGBoost

# 1. Preprocess data (Recipe)
xgb_recipe <- 
  recipe( formula = price ~ availability_365 + log_calculated_host_listings_count + log_minimum_nights + number_of_reviews + reviews_per_month + neighbourhood + distance_center + room_type, data = train ) %>% 
  step_novel( all_nominal_predictors() ) %>% # assign a previously unseen factor level to a new value
  step_lencode_mixed(neighbourhood, outcome = vars(price)) %>% 
  step_lencode_mixed(room_type, outcome = vars(price)) %>%
  step_zv( all_predictors() ) %>%  # remove variables that contain only a single value
  step_normalize( all_predictors() ) # scale predictors only

# 2. Specify model
xgb_spec <- boost_tree(
  trees = 300, ## runtime
  tree_depth = tune(), min_n = tune(), 
  loss_reduction = tune(),                     ## first three: model complexity
  sample_size = tune(), mtry = tune(),         ## randomness
  learn_rate = tune(),                         ## step size
) %>% 
  set_engine( "xgboost", early_stopping_rounds = 30 ) %>% 
  set_mode( "regression" )

# 3. Create workflow
xgb_wf <- workflow() %>%
  add_recipe( xgb_recipe ) %>%
  add_model( xgb_spec )

# 4. Do cross validation
set.seed(9)
fold <- vfold_cv( train, v = 10 )

# 5. Define values to be explored
xgb_grid <- grid_latin_hypercube(
  tree_depth(),
  min_n(),
  loss_reduction(),
  sample_size = sample_prop(),
  finalize(mtry(), train),
  learn_rate(),
  size = 20) ## runtime
## Warning: `grid_latin_hypercube()` was deprecated in dials 1.3.0.
##  Please use `grid_space_filling()` instead.
## This warning is displayed once every 8 hours.
## Call `lifecycle::last_lifecycle_warnings()` to see where this warning was
## generated.
# 6. Tune model
closeAllConnections()
doParallel::registerDoParallel(cores = parallel::detectCores() - 1)
xgb_res <- tune_grid(
xgb_wf,
resamples = fold,
grid = xgb_grid,
control = control_grid(save_pred = FALSE, verbose = TRUE, allow_par = TRUE))

5.11 Predict for test data

Clean testing data

# Convert non-numerical variables to factor and "NA" to number
testing <- testing %>%
  mutate(host_id = as.factor(host_id),
         neighbourhood = as.factor(neighbourhood),
         room_type = as.factor(room_type),
         last_review = ymd(last_review),
         reviews_per_month = ifelse(is.na(reviews_per_month), 0, reviews_per_month)
         )

# Calculate the distance to city center
testing <- testing %>%
  mutate(distance_center = distHaversine(
    cbind(longitude, latitude),
    c(lon_center, lat_center) ) / 1000) # Create new variable: distance_center (Unit: km)

# Handling outliers using the IQR technique
cols <- c("availability_365", "reviews_per_month", 
          "number_of_reviews", "minimum_nights", "calculated_host_listings_count","distance_center")

bounds <- list()
for (i in cols) {
  Q1 <- quantile(training[[i]], 0.25, na.rm = TRUE)
  Q3 <- quantile(training[[i]], 0.75, na.rm = TRUE)
  IQR <- Q3 - Q1
  
  bounds[[i]] <- list(
    lower = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR,
    upper = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
  )
}
# Replace outliers by lower or upper bounds
  testing_clean <- testing
    for (i in cols) {
      lower_bound <- bounds[[i]]$lower
      upper_bound <- bounds[[i]]$upper
    
  testing_clean <- testing_clean %>%
    mutate(
      !!i := case_when(
      .data[[i]] < lower_bound ~ lower_bound,
      .data[[i]] > upper_bound ~ upper_bound,
      TRUE ~ .data[[i]]
      )
    )
}

  
# Log transformation to reduce the skewness which is larger than 1
testing_clean <- testing_clean %>%
  mutate(
         calculated_host_listings_count = replace(calculated_host_listings_count, 
                                                  calculated_host_listings_count == 0, 0.00001),
         minimum_nights = replace(minimum_nights, minimum_nights == 0, 0.00001),
         number_of_reviews = replace(number_of_reviews, number_of_reviews == 0, 0.00001)) %>% 
  mutate(
         log_calculated_host_listings_count = log(calculated_host_listings_count), 
         log_minimum_nights = log(minimum_nights), 
         log_number_of_reviews = log(number_of_reviews),
         )

# 1. Preprocess data (Recipe)
rf_recipe <- 
  recipe(formula = price ~ availability_365 + log_calculated_host_listings_count + log_minimum_nights + number_of_reviews + reviews_per_month + neighbourhood + distance_center + room_type, data = training_clean ) %>% 
  step_novel( all_nominal_predictors() ) %>% # assign a previously unseen factor level to a new value
  step_lencode_mixed(neighbourhood, outcome = vars(price)) %>% 
  step_lencode_mixed(room_type, outcome = vars(price)) %>%
  #step_dummy( all_nominal_predictors() ) %>% 
  step_zv( all_predictors() ) %>%  # remove variables that contain only a single value
  step_normalize( all_predictors() ) # scale predictors only
